  "text": "Stack protection mechanisms in LLVM are implemented across multiple files in the llvm-project repository. The primary stack protection implementations are:\n\n### 1. StackProtector Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/StackProtector.cpp)\nThe main LLVM pass that inserts stack protector checks into functions. This file contains:\n- **StackProtectorPass**: The new PassInfoMixin-based pass class for use with the new PassManager\n- **StackProtector**: The legacy FunctionPass class for backward compatibility\n- **InsertStackProtectors()**: Core static function that performs the actual insertion of prologue code (which stores a random canary to the stack) and epilogue code (which checks if the canary has been modified and calls __stack_chk_fail if it has). The function generates code that stores a random value onto the stack before local variables are allocated and checks this value upon exiting, calling __stack_chk_fail if it has changed.\n- **CreateFailBB()**: Creates a basic block for failure handling that invokes __stack_chk_fail\n- **SSPLayoutAnalysis** and **SSPLayoutInfo**: Analysis pass and info class that determine which functions require stack protection based on buffer sizes, variable types, and function attributes\n\nKey methods:\n- `PreservedAnalyses StackProtectorPass::run(Function &F, FunctionAnalysisManager &FAM)`: New-style pass entry point\n- `bool StackProtector::runOnFunction(Function &Fn)`: Legacy pass entry point\n- The pass requires the LibcallLoweringInfo analysis to determine the appropriate runtime library calls to use\n\n### 2. SafeStack Pass (llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStack.cpp)\nImplements the SafeStack pass that separates stack allocations into safe and unsafe stacks to prevent certain classes of buffer overflow attacks. This file contains:\n- **SafeStackPass**: The new pass infrastructure class\n- **SafeStack**: The main implementation class that performs the actual stack separation work\n- **SafeStackLegacyPass**: The legacy FunctionPass wrapper\n\nKey methods in SafeStack class:\n- `SafeStack::run()`: Main entry point that orchestrates the safe/unsafe stack separation\n- `SafeStack::findInsts()`: Locates all static allocas, dynamic allocas, return instructions, and stack restore points\n- `SafeStack::moveStaticAllocasToUnsafeStack()`: Allocates space for unsafe static allocas on the unsafe stack\n- `SafeStack::moveDynamicAllocasToUnsafeStack()`: Replaces dynamic allocas with runtime allocation on the unsafe stack\n- `SafeStack::checkStackGuard()`: Validates stack guard consistency and calls __stack_chk_fail if compromised\n- `SafeStack::getStackGuard()`: Retrieves the current stack canary value\n- `SafeStack::IsSafeStackAlloca()`: Determines whether an allocation is safe or requires unsafe stack separation\n\nThe SafeStack implementation splits the stack into two regions:\n- **Safe Stack**: Regular stack for memory-safe accesses\n- **Unsafe Stack**: Explicitly allocated and managed stack for unsafe access patterns\n\n### 3. Header Files\n**llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/StackProtector.h** declares:\n- `class SSPLayoutInfo`: Information about required stack protection layout for a function\n- `class SSPLayoutAnalysis`: Analysis pass that determines stack protection requirements\n- `class StackProtectorPass`: The new-style pass interface\n\n**llvm/include/llvm/CodeGen/SafeStack.h** declares:\n- `class SafeStackPass`: New pass infrastructure interface with `run(Function &F, FunctionAnalysisManager &FAM)` method\n\n### 4. SafeStack Layout Classes\n**llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.h** declares:\n- `class StackLayout`: Computes the layout of unsafe stack frames, managing stack regions and object placement\n\n**llvm/lib/CodeGen/SafeStackLayout.cpp** implements:\n- `StackLayout::addObject()`: Adds objects to the stack layout\n- `StackLayout::layoutObject()`: Places objects in stack regions with proper alignment\n- Stack region management for coloring and efficient space usage\n\n### 5. __stack_chk_fail Runtime Implementation\n**libc/src/compiler/generic/__stack_chk_fail.cpp** provides:\n- `void __stack_chk_fail(void)`: The runtime function called when a stack protector check fails. This is a [[noreturn]] function that:\n  1. Writes \"stack smashing detected\\n\" to stderr via `LIBC_NAMESPACE::write_to_stderr()`\n  2. Calls `LIBC_NAMESPACE::abort()` to terminate the program\n  3. Defines `__stack_chk_guard`: The global canary value used for stack protector checks (initialized to 0xa9fff01234)\n\n**libc/src/compiler/__stack_chk_fail.h** declares:\n- The `extern \"C\"` declaration of the `__stack_chk_fail()` function\n\n### Instrumentation Integration\nWhile there is no dedicated stack frame protection instrumentation pass in `llvm/lib/Transforms/Instrumentation/`, the stack protection is integrated through:\n- **StackProtector** pass running in the code generation pipeline (CodeGen phase)\n- **SafeStack** pass running as a CodeGen pass\n- **AddressSanitizer.cpp** and **HWAddressSanitizer.cpp** in the Instrumentation directory include stack safety analysis integration (ClUseStackSafety flag) that leverages stack safety information to avoid redundant instrumentation\n\n### Architecture Summary\nThe stack protection mechanism works as follows:\n1. **Analysis Phase**: SSPLayoutAnalysis determines which functions require protection based on function attributes and local variable types\n2. **Insertion Phase** (StackProtector): \n   - Prologue: Loads a random canary from the stack guard global and stores it onto the function's stack\n   - Epilogue: Reloads and compares the stored canary; if modified, creates a call to __stack_chk_fail\n3. **Safe Stack Separation** (SafeStack): Identifies unsafe memory access patterns and moves those allocations to a separately managed unsafe stack\n4. **Layout** (SafeStackLayout): Manages efficient placement of stack objects with proper alignment\n5. **Runtime** (__stack_chk_fail): Handles detection and reports stack smashing attacks\n\nThese mechanisms combine to provide defense-in-depth against stack buffer overflow attacks in compiled code."
}

